      <div xml:id="NA347-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiyātu neṭuṅ kālam vantoḻuka āṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaḷait tōḻi vaṟpuṟukka maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante refused to encourage HER who was unable to bear it when [HE] kept coming for a long time without marrying.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA347">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>muḻaṅkukaṭaṉ mukanta kamañcūṉ māmaḻai</l>
<l>mātira naṉantalai putaiyap pāa</l>
<l>yōṅkuvarai miḷira vāṭṭip pāmpeṟipu</l>
<l>vāṉpuku talaiya kuṉṟa muṟṟi</l>
<l>yaḻituḷi talaiiya poḻutiṟ pulaiyaṉ 5</l>
<l>pēḻvāyt taṇṇumai yiṭantoṭ ṭaṉṉa</l>
<l>varuvi yiḻitarum peruvarai nāṭa</l>
<l>ṉiṉṉa nilaiyaṉ pēraṉ piṉaṉeṉap</l>
<l>paṉmāṇ kūṟum paricilar neṭumoḻi</l>
<l>vēṉiṟ ṟēraiyi ṉaḷiya</l>
<l>kāṇa viṭumō tōḻiyeṉ ṉalaṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>“The man from a land of great mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent4">	where the waterfalls tumble down</l>
<l rend="indent2">	as if the drummer touched the surface of the large-mouthed</l>
<l rend="indent2"> 	Taṇṇumai drum,</l>
<l>	at a time that the fully pregnant dark clouds, that drew [water] from</l>
<l rend="indent">	the thundering sea, spread, for the vast area of the great directions</l>
<l>	to be buried, driving [along] for the high mountains to be turned</l>
<l>	[upside down],</l>
<l rend="indent">	troubling snakes, maturing in the hills with heads that enter the sky,</l>
<l>	have begun to offer dwindling drops,</l>
<l>[is] in such a state, he [is] of great loving”,</l>
<l>– [these] persistent(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">neṭu moḻi</term>: what can the attribute <term xml:lang="ta">neṭu</term>, "long", mean in connection with words? Is it long-winded speeches? Or a long-lasting attempt at persuasion, i.e. persistent words?</note> words of solicitors talking of [his] many glories</l>
<l>[are] pitiable as frogs in the summer.</l>
<l>Will it visibly quit [me], friend, my beauty?<note place="foot">Actually the construction of the last two lines is far from clear, as is the object of <term xml:lang="ta">kāṇa</term> and thus the message. Tradition reads <term xml:lang="ta">aḷiya</term> as an attribute to <term xml:lang="ta">nalaṉ</term>, and then the words as object of <term xml:lang="ta">kāṇa</term> ("will my <term xml:lang="ta">nalaṉ</term>, pitiable ..., allow me to see the words ...". But one does not see words in the <term xml:lang="ta">Caṅkam</term> universe.</note></l>
        </lg>
      </div>
